inscription.text: The greatest heat in shade reached 71.5 in 1852, and only 52.9 in 1855, giving a range of 18.6 in greatest heat for March during the past eighteen years. The greatest cold was as low as 13 in 1845 (descending 1 below zero on the grass), and never below 31.0 in 1842, giving a range of 18.0 for March during the past eighteen years. The coldest years were 1845, 1846, 1848, and 1851. Only 0.3 inch of rain fell in March, 1850, and as much as 3.9 inches in 1848, giving a range of 3.6 inches, or about 3 1/2 inches for March during the past seventeen years. In eight years the fall did not exceed an inch, and in four years it was two inches and upwards. The mean fall of rain for March is 1.4 inches. March is a changeable month, the range of temperaturre being under 30 in 1842, 1846, and 1851, and being 53 in 1858, and 53.5 in 1852. It is subject to gales of wind. E.J. Lowe.
